[[File:Kuhn & Komor Shanghai Palace Hotel.jpg|thumb|Kuhn & Komor shop at the Shanghai Palace Hotel]] [[File:Kuhn & Komor Yokohama.jpg|thumb|Interior of the shop in Yokohama]] '''Kuhn & Komor''' ({{lang-ja|康茂洋行}}), also known colloquially as ''K&K'', was a Hungarian multinational luxury jewelry and specialty retailer, having headquarters in Shanghai, China. K&K produced jewelry, sterling silver, china, crystal, stationery, and personal accessories. K&K was renowned in East Asia for its luxury goods, also being called the "[[Asprey]] of Asia."<ref>http://naturalisticspoon.com/Kuhn_And_Komor.html</ref>
== History == The Komor family was Jewish and originally came from Hungary.<ref>http://digitalassets.ushmm.org/photoarchives/detail.aspx?id=1131191</ref>
Moritz Montague Kuhn founded Kuhn & Co in Yokohama in 1869, a shop filled with ''Curios'', curiosities from the Far East (or souvernirs shop). Siegfried Komo, the nephew of Kuhn, came to Japan in 1887 to work for his uncle, followed by the son ok Kuhn, Arthur, who arrived in Japan in 1890. In 1894, Siegfried Komo and Arthur Kuhn founded Kuhn & Komor in Yokohama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smokingsamurai.com/KUHN_KOMOR.html|title=KUHN & KOMOR 康茂洋行 (1869-1930)|website=Smokingsamurai.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>
The company opened a shop in the [[Shanghai Palace Hotel]] in Shanghai. They later opened a shop on No. 37 Water Street (水町通り) in [[Yokohama]].<ref>http://www.inherited-values.com/2011/10/antique-japan-travel-guide-for-westerners/</ref> The company existed roughly until the 1930s, when the outbreak of World War II brought it to an end.<ref>http://www.mjgk.com/1/gazdasagikapcsolat/148-kuhnandkomor</ref>
Items by Kuhn & Komor receive high prices on auctions.<ref>http://www.bonhams.com/auctions/21861/lot/383/</ref>
